    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/5241958541/lesson-108-urdu-consonants-part-1-ب-be" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="So what did we learn last time&nbsp;we looked at Urdu? That&rsquo;s right, we learnt all about two more Urduvowels, which were&nbsp;i and ee. We also learnt another letter of the Urdu alphabet, &#1740; chotee ye - Small Y. If you&rsquo;ve forgotten anything (and I do admit it was quite a while ago!) then head back over to&nbsp;Urdu Vowels Part 2&nbsp;and revise over what we did!&nbsp;In today&rsquo;s lesson we&rsquo;re going to learn just one more Urdu consonant! (How easy can you get, hey!).&nbsp;


&nbsp;bandar - Monkey


 By the end of this lesson you should be able to recognize the first letter in this word! (Don&rsquo;t worry about all the other letters for now, we&rsquo;ll get there eventually!)


 So are you ready to get straight into it?


&nbsp;be&nbsp;


 This is the letter we&rsquo;re going to look at today.&nbsp;This is the letter &#1576; be (Rhymes with &lsquo;hey&rsquo;), it makes a normal 'b&rsquo; sound just like the english b in boat. And this letter looks a little bit like a boat don&rsquo;t you think? There&rsquo;s also something very important to note - it has one dot underneath it! This letter is 'equivalent&rsquo; to the Hindi &#2348; ba.


 Now can you remember back to An Introduction to the Urdu Alphabet&nbsp;I said that each letter has different 'forms&rsquo; and takes a slightly different shape depending on where it is in the a word. be is no different, so we have to learn how it&rsquo;s shape changes! When it&rsquo;s in the middle or at the start of a word, it gets a little squashed, so for example&hellip;


&nbsp;baagh - Garden&nbsp;&nbsp;


 Can you see the one dot underneath the first letter of the word? (Remember we start on the right and read to the left!) That&rsquo;s the squashed up&nbsp;be! It just looks like a little hook with a dot underneath, easy! Whenever be is at the start of a word it must take this little hook shape!


 Hopefully you remember from Urdu Vowels Part 1 that the little dash above the be follow by an alif means we pronounce it baa. Don&rsquo;t worry if you&rsquo;re confused about the last letter of this word for now we&rsquo;ll learn about it later!


 So how does be look in the middle of a word? Well it actually looks very similar to how it does at the start! So for example&hellip;


&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;akhbaar&nbsp;&nbsp;- Newspaper


 Can you see the little hook and the one dot underneath? That&rsquo;s the be again! You should also be able to spot the alif after again too. Whenever be is in the middle of a word it must take this hook shape!&nbsp;


 One more word then, this time we&rsquo;ll have be at the end. When it&rsquo;s at the end of a word be stretches back out to normal again, like in the Urdu word&hellip;


&nbsp;kab&nbsp;&nbsp;- When &nbsp;


 Can you see now that the&nbsp;be at the end isn&rsquo;t just a little hook - it&rsquo;s the big boat shape again? Whenever be is at the end it must take this boat shape!&nbsp;


 Are you starting to get the hang of this? Make sure you have a good look at each word as we go through them, it&rsquo;s important for you to see the shape of the letter each time! Ready for some more examples? &nbsp;


&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;baithnaa - To Sit


 This words a little more complicated but all you need to focus on is the first letter. Can you see the little hook with a dot underneath at the start? That&rsquo;s our&nbsp;be!


&nbsp;caabee - Key


 (Note 'c&rsquo; is pronounced 'ch&rsquo; like in church). Woah, ok so whats happened here? There&rsquo;s no little hook? Well can you see the one dot underneath in the middle of the word? That&rsquo;s our be! But because it comes after an alif it doesn&rsquo;t join on to the previous part (Remember an alif never joins to the next letter!) and because it comes before a chotee ye the be sits above the line. All you need to notice is the dot underneath!&nbsp;


&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;taaalaab - Pond


 Can you spot the be this time? That&rsquo;s right, it&rsquo;s just sitting at the end, and because it&rsquo;s at the end it&rsquo;s back to the boat shape!


 Do you think you&rsquo;ve understood this lesson? If you have any questions then please feel free to ask me in the comments section below!&nbsp;Do you think you&rsquo;re ready to spot the letter&nbsp;be&nbsp;in some words? Just below are five Urdu words, I want you to see if you can spot the letter be in each of them. If you get stuck be sure to leave me a comment below!


 &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Child &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Language&nbsp;


 &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Ill &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Student


 &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 5.&nbsp;&nbsp;- Sometime


 Did you spot a be in each of those words? Some of them are harder than others. Leave a comment if you&rsquo;re confused and I&rsquo;ll do my best to help you!


 So well done for reaching the end of this lessons, there&rsquo;s been a lot of crazy letters that we haven&rsquo;t met yet, but unfortunately you have to start somewhere. Next time we&rsquo;re going to look a few more Consonants - but you may be surprised, they&rsquo;ll be a lot easier than you think!


 Back to the Urdu Section." property="og:description" /><meta content="Lesson #108: Urdu Consonants Part 1; ب be" property="og:title" /><style type="text/css">p.center { text-align: center; }

